bug.short_desc: Full-blown website builds, proof of concept and consideration

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1260 proof of concept
************************************************************* Full-blown website builds, proof of concept and consideration *************************************************************
With over 5 years of qooxdoo desktop experience I have been enjoying design, stability, intuitive APIs, powerful tool-chain, features on the heels of web technology and so on and so forth. And every time I needed to come out of this familiar realm into the wild of common javascript front-end development [1]_ I was unwilling and saddened.
As-is =====
Since first time I've seen qxWeb initiative I was really exited. After some precise look and experiments I found that the state of affairs is pretty much differs from my expectations:
* Devoid from full-blown build system, * Most importantly dependency management and partial builds, * Uses manual ``qx.module.*`` to bridge the subset of the library, * Uncertain code management and deployment guidelines.
Overall I would say that the mission qxWeb is uncertain at the moment. We all know how jQuery-like libraries changed the web. They are known and serve the certain needs, basically, the needs of cross-browser DOM-patching and asynchronous networking. Say, a layout coder in addition to his HTML and CSS, adds a few lines of javascript to animate a menu with jQuery plugin or to show a popping overlay. In a little more complex case some networking is involved.
These libraries work just fine for their audience and there's no much to fix. There are tons of documentation, articles, plugins, snippets for them. I doubt there's a reason or a niche for yet another one, which addresses the same problems with different syntax.
To-be =====
"Don't just look at the widgets, look at the development tools as well" [2]_, – Fabian Jakobs. In fact qooxdoo tooling is the killer feature. Class system, dependency management, partial builds, test infrastructure, lint, configuration, and many other features from tool-chain. This is what is really required at mid- and high-scale website development when it's not widget-based and qooxdoo desktop isn't appropriate.
I'll draft some basic requirements:
* Full-featured qooxdoo class system, * Full-featured qooxdoo build system, * Common access to non-UI part of library, * Source and build version, * Flexible part loading, * External library inclusion with dependency management, * Easy API for DOM operations.
The solution is easy and has been around for some time (since ``source-hybrid`` was introduced). Starting from pre 3.0 it's self contained and doesn't require external tools. What fulfills the above requirements is **qooxdoo native + qxWeb**. Not straight out of the box, but with minimal application logic and configuration.
Proof of concept ================
For a back-end I've created a exemplary website of 4 pages with cherrypy. The code of back-end and front-end is `here <code.google.com/p/qooxdoo-website-skeleton/>`_. For quick peek I've build a python package (tested on python 2.6 and 2.7), see attachment. Installation. ::
virtualenv demo . demo/bin/activate pip install /path/to/archive/qws-0.1.0.zip python demo/bin/cherryd -i website.serve
After point your browser to http://localhost:8005/. This will work with pre-built javascript. To run in source mode and make changes see the next section.
Now briefly about pages and their load: * ``/``. *Menu* controller is included statically in the boot package [3]_. * ``/gallery``. *Gallery* controller is load by route. It requires ``website.library.MosaicFlow`` which in turn requires ``website.library.Jquery``. * ``/article``. Loads Disqus script in controller constructor. The template includes a part [4]_ which loads ``Selectable`` controller on demand. * ``/geo``. Loads OpenLayers library, and creates a map when it's loaded.
The entity that holds a user code I called a controller. There should be two expectations about a controller: * could be instantiated before ``DOMContentLoaded``, * ``main`` method is called after ``DOMContentLoaded``.
So the code should be arranged accordingly.
Every controller should be described in configuration file under ``jobs.common.packages`` and in ``Application`` class ``JSDoc`` comment.
There are three load types for a controller: * **static**, described with ``@require`` in ``Application`` class and in ``_immediate`` array field, * **fixed route**, described with ``@use`` in ``Application`` class and in ``_fixed`` map field by the regular expression which matches on URLs (``window.location.pathname`` actually) that should be served by the controller, * **on-demand** described with ``@use`` in ``Application`` class and added to ``qx.$$loadPackages`` in a template.
Consider the ``min-package`` and ``min-package-unshared`` configuration keys under ``jobs.common.packages``. They will affect how packages are merged. Tuning their values will result in different package layout.
Note that in source mode the boot package doesn't carry any user code, so everything loaded in runtime.
Setting up workspace ====================
To run the site in source mode and make change clone `front-end repository <https://code.google.com/p/qooxdoo-website-skeleton.frontend>`_. Change paths in ``config.json`` and ``generate.py`` to match your local qooxdoo master-branch directory. Change ``qx.sourceRoot`` environment key so it match your filesystem layout (webserver root is your filesystem root). Then run::
generate.py generate.py source-server
Then clone `backend-end repository <https://code.google.com/p/qooxdoo-website-skeleton.backend>`_. It's a good idea to create a virtual environment for it::
virtualenv backend . backend/bin/activate pip install cherrypy pip install jinja2
Now copy ``website`` folder in virtual environment's folder and run::
python backend/bin/cherryd -i serve -P backend/website
For source mode script tag in main layout should point to ``http://localhost:2436/your/path/to/frontend/source/script/website.js``. For build to ``/resource/js/website.js``. When rebuilt, files should be placed into ``public/resource/js``.
Related bugs ============
#7182 – generator console gets bloated by ``Warning: Unable to parse JSDoc entry`` which currently there's no way to suppress.
#6968 - reopened because @ignore doesn't work with external libraries.
#6709, #6616 – there's workaround with ``decode-uris-plug``.
#6638 – likely to set to WONTFIX.
Bug candidates ==============
There were some cases during this experiment that could be a bug. Confirm, and I will file them.
1. qxWeb and event.preventDefault() e.g. ::
q('a#test').on('click', function(event) { event.preventDefault(); // will fail in IE qx.bom.Event.preventDefault(event); // this works everywhere });
2. qxWeb and event listener for DOM events like ``DOMSubtreeModified``. Listener won't work with q('#smth').on('DOMSubtreeModified'...
3. qxWeb and event objects. These object are low level. Is there's any reason to use ``qx.module.event`` instead of ``qx.event`` layer? Overhead?
4. Can't use ``${SOURCE_SERVER_PORT}`` in environment variable definition. Change ``qx.sourceRoot`` to something like ``http://localhost:${APPLICATION}/a/b/c`` in the example and build will fail with ::
<type 'exceptions.ValueError'> : Macro left undefined in job (source-hybrid::source-script): 'SOURCE_SERVER_PORT' (might be from an included config)
Further consideration =====================
Well, most important thing is that this approach works! My example just provides one possible implementation.
In my point of view this kind of full-build website development is more natural for qooxdoo projects as desktop and mobile does use full-build. If some of my point are considered practical there are some further consideration.
Boilerplate vs fine-grained configuration -----------------------------------------
To add a controller, in terminology of my example, there are 3 changes required: 1 in config, 2 in Application. qxWeb modules are also need to be included manually. This could be seen from either side.
qx.* vs q.* -----------
In full-build case qxWeb is a convenience thing which provides shortcuts to functions which make sense to be shortcutted [5]_. Of course DOM operation like selector queries, traversals, attribute management. Animation and templating looks reasonable as well.
However some functionality that qxWeb currently provides deals with low level objects and events. For example, how would seriously want to write something like
::
q.io.xhr("script/qxWeb.json").send().on("loadend", function(xhr) { if(xhr.readyState == 4 && xhr.status >= 200 && xhr.status < 400) { var data = JSON.parse(xhr.responseText); // use data } else { // handle error } });
instead of
::
var request = new qx.io.request.Xhr('script/qxWeb.json'); request.addListener('success', function(event) { var data = event.getTarget().getResponse(); // use data }, this); request.addListener('fail', function(event) { // handle error }, this); request.send();
So I think some parts of qxWeb could be considered redundant where corresponding qx.* object could be used just fine. For instance: networking, class definition, local storage, utils. It's something to think about.
Integration -----------
It could be somewhat ``qx.application.Website`` with basic router, maybe a bit more advanced than in my example. With predefined application structure (skeleton for create-application.py) it could be easier for end-users to get grasp of. Some guideline for wrapping external libraries could be a good idea as well.
Major feel of major change, version 3.0 :-)
-----------------
.. [1] HTML and CSS as presentation layer, javascript logic in dozens of classes, various libraries in various pages, source and build versions, etc, in contrast to inline per-page DOM-patching scenario. .. [2] http://www.slideshare.net/fjakobs/masterin-large-scale-java-script-applications .. [3] The javascript file that is included in a page. .. [4] A page part that has no fixed URL and could be included in various pages. .. [5] Since ``qx.bom.Collection`` is deprecated and likely be removed in 3.0 the assumption isn't fully correct.
Thanks for the report. Your feedback is always welcome. It might take some time for me to get a appropriate answer, as we are already in the pre release phase.

(In reply to comment #0) > Bug candidates > ============== > > There were some cases during this experiment that could be a bug. Confirm, and > I will file them. > > 1. qxWeb and event.preventDefault() e.g. :: > > q('a#test').on('click', function(event) > { > event.preventDefault(); // will fail in IE > qx.bom.Event.preventDefault(event); // this works everywhere > });
Looks like you did not load the 'qx.module.event.Native' module which should normalize that for IE.
> 2. qxWeb and event listener for DOM events like ``DOMSubtreeModified``. > Listener won't work with q('#smth').on('DOMSubtreeModified'...
If the browser supports that event and we are able to detect it, it should work. If you can supply a sample to demonstrate, its a bug and we would be happy if you open a separate report for that.
> 3. qxWeb and event objects. These object are low level. Is there's any reason > to use ``qx.module.event`` instead of ``qx.event`` layer? Overhead?
Its the overhead. We have to consider the file size of the library so we can't use any class based on qx.Class at the moment without increasing the file size.
> 4. Can't use ``${SOURCE_SERVER_PORT}`` in environment variable definition. > Change ``qx.sourceRoot`` to something like > ``http://localhost:${APPLICATION}/a/b/c`` in the example and build will fail > with :: > > <type 'exceptions.ValueError'> : Macro left undefined in job > (source-hybrid::source-script): 'SOURCE_SERVER_PORT' > (might be from an included config)
Looks like you have overridden the let definition of the 'source-server' job, right? Because the macro is defined in the job itself and should work as expected.
> :: > > q.io.xhr("script/qxWeb.json").send().on("loadend", function(xhr) > { > if(xhr.readyState == 4 && xhr.status >= 200 && xhr.status < 400) > { > var data = JSON.parse(xhr.responseText); > // use data > } > else > { > // handle error > } > }); > > instead of > > :: > > var request = new qx.io.request.Xhr('script/qxWeb.json'); > request.addListener('success', function(event) > { > var data = event.getTarget().getResponse(); > // use data > }, this); > request.addListener('fail', function(event) > { > // handle error > }, this); > request.send();
Sure, the XHR could be more convenient. At the moment, it is as close as possible to the XHR spec but we could enhance the whole thing. Could you open up a bug report for that?
> It could be somewhat ``qx.application.Website`` with basic router, maybe a bit > more advanced than in my example. With predefined application structure > (skeleton for create-application.py) it could be easier for end-users to get > grasp of. Some guideline for wrapping external libraries could be a good idea > as well.
The skeletons should be overhauled but we don't have a exact idea whats missing and what should be added. We already thought about something like a MVC structure but are not at a point where we have anything to show.

> Looks like you did not load the 'qx.module.event.Native' module which should normalize that for IE.
You're right. Richard has recently fixed #7667. So it's possible now.
> If the browser supports that event and we are able to detect it, it should work. If you can supply a sample to demonstrate, its a bug and we would be happy if you open a separate report for that.
There you go: #8083
> Its the overhead. We have to consider the file size of the library so we can't use any class based on qx.Class at the moment without increasing the file size.
I see.
> Looks like you have overridden the let definition of the 'source-server' job, right? Because the macro is defined in the job itself and should work as expected.
No, I didn't override 'source-server'. Even though I don't get the second sentence, and 3.0.2 is affected, 3.5 is not. So it has probably been fixed.
> Sure, the XHR could be more convenient. At the moment, it is as close as possible to the XHR spec but we could enhance the whole thing. Could you open up a bug report for that?
Eh, long there #6601. Assigned to some guy, called Martin Wittemann ;-)
> The skeletons should be overhauled but we don't have a exact idea whats missing and what should be added. We already thought about something like a MVC structure but are not at a point where we have anything to show.
After your reply, I've been spending some time peeping around this MVC/MVVM/another-prominent-pattern javascript libraries. Just because I'm using the approach the bugreport proposes and most basic things are already covered the more advanced topics come to the perspective. Specifically, I sketched, something like ``qx.data.controller.website.List``, then later, oops, found qooxdoo already has one ;-) This approach is good for prototyping, but for a production UI, it has several well-known shortcomings. So if I end up with certain concept I like, I'll post it here with some background.
Move open issues to RESOLVED – LATER, whose last comment is older than a year.
